### SAT Core Tools

<a name="sat-core-tools"></a>

These tools exist **for SAT itself**.

- Manage SAT versions, schemas, and invariants
- Never touch archive content
- Ensure SAT remains coherent as a system
- Used by SAT developers, not archive authors

They define what SAT *is*, not what archives contain.

[Return to chart](#sat-tools-architecture-chart)

### Archive Tools

<a name="archive-tools"></a>

Archive tools operate on **archive boundaries**.

- Create and validate archive identity
- Enforce structural expectations
- Resolve configuration explicitly
- Never infer meaning from content

They are the primary interface between SAT and archives.

[Return to chart](#sat-tools-architecture-chart)

### Content Tools

<a name="content-tools"></a>

Content tools assist **humans working with meaning**.

- Help generate compliant metadata
- Validate content without interpreting it
- Support imports and transformations
- Respect linguistic and structural divergence

They serve people first, SAT second.

[Return to chart](#sat-tools-architecture-chart)

### Publication Utilities

<a name="publication-utilities"></a>

Publication utilities produce **outputs**, not truth.

- Consume prepared archives
- Apply renderer-specific logic
- Are optional and replaceable
- Never influence archive validity

Outputs are temporary. Archives are not.

[Return to chart](#sat-tools-architecture-chart)

